Set Up

Here we get the dataset set up and define the laziness decay function.

{% raw %} 
import diffusion_curvature # our main package
from diffusion_curvature.core import plot_3d, DiffusionMatrix
from diffusion_curvature.laziness import curvature, local_laziness
import numpy as np
{% endraw %}

Let's establish our tried and true dataset, the torus!

{% raw %} 
from diffusion_curvature.datasets import torus
X, ks = torus(n=5000,seed=42)
P = DiffusionMatrix(X,kernel_type='adaptive anisotropic',k=20)
# the hyperparameters here are the kernel type and the kernel bandwidth. I've chosen them by hand to work well.

laziness_decay[source]

laziness_decay(A, max_steps=32, aperture=20, neighborhood=10, smoothing=1, adaptive_neighborhood=False, non_lazy_diffusion=False, use_local_laziness=False)

Generates a matrix of the decaying laziness value per point over a range of t values

Parameters

P : ndarray Diffusion matrix max_steps : int, optional Number of diffusion steps to take (starting from 1), by default 32 aperture : int, optional The size of the initial diffusion neighborhood, by default 20 smoothing : int, optional Number of smmoothing interations, by default 1

Returns

ndarray Each column is a set of laziness values per point at a specific time.

{% endraw %}

Such a small function! But such power! Let's test it on the donut. It will also be informative to see how long it takes.

{% raw %} 
%%time
decaying_lazy = laziness_decay(P, max_steps=32,aperture=20, adaptive_neighborhood=True)

CPU times: user 1min 17s, sys: 4.3 s, total: 1min 21s
Wall time: 11.7 s
{% endraw %} {% raw %} 
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
plt.plot(decaying_lazy[0])

[<matplotlib.lines.Line2D at 0x16d2c89a0>]
{% endraw %}

These laziness decay plots look just as one would expect: the laziness decays. But does it decay differently in different regions? For this, we need to identify the indices of some points on the donut.

The torus function has been set up and so that the 0th point is on the outer rim, in a region of high positive curvature. The 1st point is in the inside, in a region of negative curvature, and the 2nd point is on the top, where the curvature should be closer to zero.

But let's first verify that the laziness is tracking with the curvature here.

{% raw %} 
plot_3d(X,decaying_lazy[:,16],title="Laziness with t=16")
{% endraw %} {% raw %} 
plot_3d(X,decaying_lazy[:,16],title="Laziness with t=16",use_plotly=True)
{% endraw %}

Let's visualize our target points:

{% raw %} 
dist = np.zeros(len(X))
dist[0] = 1
dist[1] = 1
dist[2] = 1
plot_3d(X,dist,cmap="cool")
{% endraw %}

Decay Graphs, with minimal smoothing

At last, we can draw a laziness decay graph!

{% raw %} 
fig, ax = plt.subplots(1)
ax.plot(decaying_lazy[0],color='green',label='Positive')
ax.plot(decaying_lazy[2],color='blue',label='Zero')
ax.plot(decaying_lazy[1],color='red',label='Negative')
ax.legend()
ax.set_xlabel("Diffusion Time Steps")
ax.set_ylabel("Laziness")

Text(0, 0.5, 'Laziness')
{% endraw %}

As expected, the point of negative curvature decays fastest, and the positively curved point is the most leisurely.

This graph also illustrates the diffusion time steps which optimally emphasize the contrast between these points. Anywhere from 7 to 20 appears reasonable.

Studies in Absurdities

The decay graph gives us a good way of gauging what each type of diffusion matrix does -- how much powering is necessary to separate the negative and positive regions.

What if we take this to extremes though? In the example below, we build a diffusion matrix with an absurdly large kernel size -- build with standard deviation to encompass the 40th nearest neighbor. And, interestingly, this exaggerates the differences in curvature between the points. But is this an artifact of the torus? Almost surely.

{% raw %} 
X = torus(n=5000,seed=42)
P = DiffusionMatrix(X,kernel_type='adaptive',k=40)
decaying_lazy = laziness_decay(P, max_steps=32,aperture=40,adaptive_neighborhood=True)

Distance to kth neighbors [0.65620276 0.66115838 0.56620977 ... 0.58632997 0.67577124 0.61838655]
{% endraw %} {% raw %} 
fig, ax = plt.subplots(1,figsize=(10,10))
ax.plot(decaying_lazy[0],color='green',label='Positive')
ax.plot(decaying_lazy[2],color='blue',label='Zero')
ax.plot(decaying_lazy[1],color='red',label='Negative')
ax.legend()
ax.set_xlabel("Diffusion Time Steps")
ax.set_ylabel("Laziness")

Text(0, 0.5, 'Laziness')
{% endraw %}

What does this diffusion actually look like? Is it huge?

{% raw %} 
plot_3d(X,P[1],title='Diffusion with k = 40',use_plotly=False)
{% endraw %}

It's not as big as I imagined. And yet the highest contrast between regions of curvature appears when t=0, a sign that whatever this measurement is picking up is more about the "shape" of a diffusion, in the peculiar realm of the torus, than the dynamics of laziness of random walks.

Does it work in miniature?

The above shows that, for the torus, the laziness exaggerates the curvature the higher the kernel bandwidth. My suspicion is that this is exploiting some density disparities in the torus. The diffusion laziness method, as hypothesized, shouldn't work for t=1 -- and yet this does.

So what if we go the other direction and set the kernel bandwidth to its absolute minimum?

{% raw %} 
X = torus(n=5000,seed=42)
P = DiffusionMatrix(X,kernel_type='adaptive anisotropic',k=5)
decaying_lazy = laziness_decay(P, max_steps=64,aperture=5,adaptive_neighborhood=True)

Distance to kth neighbors [0.19671531 0.16551379 0.13723136 ... 0.22801285 0.16191064 0.211507  ]
{% endraw %} {% raw %} 
fig, ax = plt.subplots(1,figsize=(10,10))
ax.plot(decaying_lazy[0],color='green',label='Positive')
ax.plot(decaying_lazy[2],color='blue',label='Zero')
ax.plot(decaying_lazy[1],color='red',label='Negative')
ax.legend()
ax.set_xlabel("Diffusion Time Steps")
ax.set_ylabel("Laziness")

Text(0, 0.5, 'Laziness')
{% endraw %}

Here we observe the opposite trend: rather than starting as a perfect indicator of curvature, this starts terribly, and takes upwards of 50 diffusion steps to course correct. What does this 50 step diffusion look like?

{% raw %} 
Pt = np.linalg.matrix_power(P,50)
plot_3d(X,Pt[0],title="50 step diffusion")
{% endraw %}

Notably, this has far from caked the entire torus with diffusion -- it remains evenly wrapped mostly around the tube in which it originated.

This seems a legitimate way to measure the curvature: start with a very small kernel, and then take many, many steps to escape density.

Alternatively, start with a large kernel, and take fewer steps -- possible no steps at all!

Are these different sides of the same method, or entirely different methods?

{% raw %} 
X = torus(n=5000,seed=42)
P = DiffusionMatrix(X,kernel_type='adaptive anisotropic',k=10)
decaying_lazy = laziness_decay(P, max_steps=64,aperture=10,adaptive_neighborhood=True)
